{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_india_ver02/data/sn83045433/100493445/1908041901/0241.xml":{"full_text":"WASHINGTON, D. C,, WASHINGTON, D. C., SUNDAY, APRIL 19, 1908.\nBUILDING\nRen ESTAT\nNEED OF BUSINESS\n10 DEVELOP CITY\nJohn L. Weaver Says Popula\ntion Is Unbalanced.\n\u2018DEFINES THREE CLASSES\n\nF\nGovernment Clerk, Negro, and\nthe Wealthy Resident.\n\nUrges Cultivation of Industry and\nTrade to Fill Up Gaps Between\nClasses with Men of Ferce and\nEnergy-Thinks City, Cannot Be\nPermanently Beautiful Otherwise.\nSuffers from Cheap Architecture.\n\n\n\nCHARTIS TUM LL nTap Aust\nThe next step that should be taken in\nthe development of Greater Washington\nis to provide what might be called in lieu\nof a betier term a balanced population.\nExpression was given to this idea by\nJohn L. Weaver at the last meeting of\nthe Washington Chamber of Commerce,\nwhen he urged it to fill the office of active\nsecretary.\nMr. Weaver spcke at length in explana\ntion of his motion and in defense of tak\ning a bold step forward in an effort to\nfurther not only Washington's commer\ncial development, but the building of a\nbeautiful city. He stated that the popu\nlation of Washington consisted of three\nisolated groups, separate and distinct,\nwith no relation of mutuality between\nthem. There is separating them great\ngaps that might be filled to advantage\nto the existing population and to the\ncity itseif.\nThree Classes of People,\nMr. Weaver classed these three groups\nas follows:\nFirst\u2014The government employes, num\nbering about 30,000 wage earners, with\nthose depending upon them, making an\naggregate of about 150,000 souls. To this\nclass he added the business eiement, as\nits status toward Washington is prac\ntically the same as that of the govern\nment employe.\nSecond\u2014-The negro element, numbering\nabout 100,000,\nThird\u2014The wealthy class, small in num\nber,\nIn discussing these classes it was Mr,\nWeaver's opinion that the government\nemploye, with his dependable salary, is\nthe element in Washington's composition\nthat keeps it alive and progressive. The\ngovernment empiloye\u2019's average earnings\ncf $1,200 per annum is subject to no\nstrikes, lockouts, or other labor troubles.\nHe is never laid off because of \u201chard\ntimes\u201d or other kindred reasons, and he\nis always paid in cash\u2014-no clearing-house\ncertificates, certified checks, or other\nforms of emergency currency are ever\noffered him op pay day.\nNegro Element Specified,\nMr. Weaver's idea of the negro ele\nment, forming as it does one-third of\nour population, is that it contains some\nestimable citizens, but as a whole is not\ncapable of advancing our city to any ap\npreciative extent. They fill many needs\nof our community, but we are forced to\nthe conclusion that Washington has little\nor nothing to expect from this class.\nHe stated that the wealthy people are\nso few in number, yet so conspicuous in\nthe devsiopment of greater and more\nbeautiful Washington, that their position\nin our community is unique. They have\ndone more for a beautiful and artistic\ncity than any other group of citizens.\nMr. Weaver asked the question, after\nhaving clearly defined the three groups,\n\u201cWhat can be done to secure those two\nother groups of citizens found in every\n\u2018other growing city, the prosperous busi\nness man ang the thrifty workman?\u201d\nMr. Weaver asserted that when Wash\nington was compared to other cities of its\ngize the number of business men and\nthrifty workmen is woefully small.\nBusiness Men Are Needed,\nIn his opinion, the business man is\nnecessary to fill in the gap between the\ngroup represented by the government em\nployes and that which he termed the\n\u2018wealthy class, and the thrifty workman\nis necessary to fill in the gap between\nthe government empioye and the negro\nelement. He then put the question, \u201cHow\ncan Washington provide these two\nclasses?\u201d He followed the question with\nthe definite and positive assertion that\nthey could be secured by Washingten\nentering upon an energetic and perse\nvering line of commercial development.\nMr. Weaver stated that to bring about\nthis commercial development Washing\nton had only to adopt the methods and\nmeans employed by other cities which\nhave successfully developed themselves\nalong commercial lines.\nNeed Not Be Experimental,\nMr, Weaver asserted that the develop\nment of commercial Washington need\nnot be an experiment; that the experi\nment had been tried with great success\niz many other cemmunities. He ex\npressed the belief that the application of\nthe usual dominant will of the Wash\nington business man to this problem must\nresult In success; that he believed the\nWashingtonian the equal, if not the su\nperior, of a great many other types of\ncitizens, and expressed the belief that it\nwas only necessary to point out to the\ncitizen of Washington his duty in the\npremises to secure action which would\nlead to ultimate success. Mr. Weaver\nlaid down the proposition that no beauti\nful Washington, worthy of the name,\ncould be expected from the population of\nthis city as now constituted, for the fol\nlowing reasons:\n\nThe negro need not be considered.\nThe government employe cannot be ex\npected to build beautiful Washington,\nbecause the average salary paid him, i.e,\n$1,200, would not justify us in expecting\nhim to do so.\n\nThe wealthy class, he pointed out, is so\nspall and their interests are 86 confined\nthat, while they are deserving of the\n\ncredit for what has been done,\nthey cannot be expected to take the same\ninterest as the man who is making, or\nhas made, his fortune in our city.\nBusiness Man Hope of City.\nHe pointed out that the successful] busi\nhe has done in cther cities, those\nhomies\nbusiness man, can be secured for Wash\nington, he will use one of the magnificent\n\u2018hills around W for his home,\n\nIf this section of our city was used,\n\u2018with its natura]~ beauty, it would be\n\u201cproperly used,\u201d rather than cut up into\nsmall lots, leveled off, thus depriving it\nof all natural beauty, and sold to the\none customer, i, e., the government em\nploye, with his comparatively small in\ncome,\n1\n\n\nIn conclusion, Mr. Weaver urged upon\nthe chamber to employ a secretary com\npetent to develop the commercial inter\nests of our city along the lines suggested.\nMr, Weaver urged that this man should\nbe one who bas had training in this par\nticular line of work; if possible, a secre\ntary from another city who has success\nfully conducted a commercial campaign.\ni\n\n\nWould Develop Self-reliance,\nMr, Weaver sounded In his speech a\nnote which might be dwelt upon until\ntha full volume of the tone should be\n\u2018heard by the people of Washington. This\nwas the cultivation of greater initiative\nand self-reliance on the part of the in\nhabitants of the city. This idea was not\nenlarged upon by Mr. Weaver, but his\nthought seemed to be that the man of\naffairs in Washington is not living up\nthe full measure of his opportunities,\nFor one thing, there is lack of concerted\naction to a given end. Men seem to be\nhesitating and fearful. They generally\nact ag though they depended on some\nbody or something for that initiative of\naction which is the chief asset of the\nsuccessful American,\n\n\n\n3 MEU RESTS SHREK\n\n\nInstead of so much dependence upon\nCongress and its appropriations, the idea\nin Mr. Weaver's mind seemed to be that\nWashingtonians should do mors for\nthemselves: knock at the doors of Con\ngress, if need be, and demand what they\nneed. At all events, there is a call for\nthe business element ang those who\nwould make the city progressive com\nmercially to bring the power of intelli\ngent, concerted effort to bear upon the\nproblems of industry and trade. There\nwill be investments to make, large enter\nprises to plan and carry to success; and\nin this age of corporate operations such\nthings cannot be accomplished by indi\nvidual or sporadic efforts.\n\n\nSomething like a campaign must be in\naugurated, with leaders and men in the\nranks to work long and faithfully to re\nmove obstacles, force the way through\nan unwilling and hestile country, and\nwrest victory from those who would keep\nWashington from the enjoyment of what\nbelongs to it.\n\nFactories Large and Small,\nIn many of the discussions of the up\nbuilding of Washington it has been sug\ngested that the best the city could hope\nfor was \u201clight manufactures,\u201d such as\nwould be secondary in their nature, could\nbe established without great outlay, and\nwould give, when established, small and\nfair profits. Hers is an evidence of this\nhesitating spirit referred to. Why small\nfactories, when there could be large\nones? Towns of one-third the size of\nWashington in the States are constantly\nbringing large industries to their pre\ncinets, establishing them, and growing\nafterward upon the benefits of such in\ndusfry.\nIt seems inexplicable that the idea\nshould be so widespread In Washington\nthat it cannot have what it wants in the\nway of industry in any other direction.\nThis eringing spirit of deference te some\nhigher political or social power scoms to\nhave unnerved a large portion of the\npeople of the Capital and to have left\nthem without initiative and that degree\nof self-reliance which has been the chief\nmoving force in the development of this\ncountry. Why should it be absent from\nthe Capital of the Nation, that is fired\nwith it from the aged patriarch to the boy\nin gingham aprons and knee breeches?\nhis address of Mr, Weaver was greet\ned with loud applause from the members\nof the Chamber of Commerce, and the\nmotion he advocated was passed without\na dissenting vote, showing that the sentl\nments which he uttered have large sym\npathy in the minds of many of the men\nof affairs in Washington\nGLEBE HIGHLANDS INVITES,\nHistorie Eiate in Virginia Will Seen\nHave Many Homes,\nOne of the historical places in the vi\ncinity of Washington is the Glebe estate\non the line of the Great Falls and Old\nDominion Railroad, in Virginia. This\nproperty was originally owned by the\nchurch, whose title came by direct grant\nfrom the King of England. It was at one\ntime the home of the Hon. Caleb Cush\ning, a former Secretary of State, and was\nlater the home of James P. Willett, who\nwas postmaster of Washington.\nJust before the death of President Me\nKinley an offer was made for the place\nby Mr. Herrick, who had intended buy\ning it for the President, to be used by\nhim as his summer home, but his assassi\nnation put an end to the negotiations.\nThe property, which contains about 100\nacres, occupies a commaning position on\nthe Virginia hills, with magnificent\nview of the city and the surrounding\ncountry. The old house, which fronts\ntoward the Mount Olivet road, is quaint\nand attractive looking, reminding one\nforeibly of the days long gone by.\nAbout twenty acres of the old estate,\nlying in West Cherrydale, at the end of\nthe one-fare limit, is now being subdivided\nand is to be known as \u201cGlebe Highlands.\u201d\nThe subdivision is to be handled by Craig\nHEvans, whose foresight in choosing the\nsection along the line of the Great Falls\nand Old Dominion Railroad for develop\nment is bringing its reward. The com\nmanding views in this country, which\nin natural beauty are unsurpassed around\nWashington, are beginning to be known\nand appreciated.\n\ni\n\n\n\n\n\nJohm M, Henderson Will Erect\nHouses on the Ground Purchased.\nThomas J. Fisher Co. Have sold, to\nJohn M. Henderson, the builder, lots\nfronting 100 feet on V street, and 0 feet\non Kalorama road, between Eighteenth\n\u2018and Nineteenth streets northwest, upon\nwhich Mr. Henderson will erect modern\nhouses for sale at a medium price. Plans\nare now being prepared and Fisher\nCo. will have the exclusive selling agency.\nFisher Co. have just closed the\nsale of the Independent Ice Company's\nplant, between the canal and the river\nand west of the Aqueduct Bridge, belong\ning to the American Ice Company. The\nplant has not been in use for a number\nof years. The price paid for the property\nis about 323,000, including improvements.\ni\n\n\nJ. J. Crane has just purchased through\nFisher Co. two lots on th: north\nside of Oliver street, in Chev. Chase,\nD. C. The property has a fruatage of\nfifty-five feet, and depth of about 1%\nfeet to a fifteen-foot aliey. Price paid is\n35 cents per square foot. Mr. Crane buys\nwith the intention of building a residence\nfor his own use in the near future,\nW. 8. Dulin has bought three lots in\nsection 3, Chevy Chase, Md., containing\nabout 20,006 square feet of ground fronting\non Taylor street. Mr. Dulin buys the\nsite for his home, and will build within\nthe next few years.\nness man would build in Washington, as\nstantial s in which Washington is\nsub\nthe office of N. L. Sansbury, three lots\nin Saul's Addition, on which he will at\nonce begin the erection of detached\nTha largest dMeoerning Cirealsticen\nAll \u201cadvertising contracts made by T) The\n\u2018Washington Herald are based upon its\nbona fide eirculation\u2014a circulation in\nWashington larger by thousands than was\never before attained by any morning\nnewspaper at the Capital Its books are\nopen,\ngo glaringly deficient, .and which cannot\nbe built by our present population, for\nthe reasons pointed out above. He stated\nthat all cities commercially developed are\nsurrounded by villas occupied by success\nful business men, which &re their great\nest charm. He expressed the opinion\n~hat if this type of citizen, the successiul\nhouses, which will be placed on the mar\nket for sale when completed. The pro\nposed houses will be two stories high,\nwith cellars and attics. The price paid\nfor the lots was $5,500.\nstory house at 30f Eleventh strest south\nJeast at an estimated cost of $3,500. J.\nBUYS V STREET LOTS.\n\"ROW OF THREE-STORY BRICK HOUSES IN SIXTEENTH STREET.\nROW\nBaa\nEp\nSou\ni\ni\n3\nen\na, RRA\nTL Bs\n\nLI\nBE a\nBE\nMARKET MORE ACTIVE\nBusiness Sites, Apartments.\nand Lots Sell Well.\nA STORE BRINGS $100,000\nNinth Street Property Closed sat 36\na Square Foot\u2014Walker Residence\nSelis for #9,500-Melwood Apart\nment Worth \u00a330,000\u2014-Deals In\nLots\u2014Notes on Bullding.\n\n\nThe real estate market has been more\nactive for the past week than for some\ntime previously. Both in the number of\nsales made and the character of the\nproperty sold, a distinct improvement nas\nbeen perceptible. Business sites, resi\ndences, lots for new buildings, apart\nments, and other kinds of property have\nentered into the operations of the week.\n\nAmong the business properties sold was\nthat at $19 to 823 Seventh street north\nwest, purchased by Henry Orth for $i00,\n000. The property occupies three lots in\nsquare 53, and a five-story building stands\nupon the lots, used as a furniture store.\nThe purchaser will hold the property as\nan investment, having purchased the\nlease with the property. The deal was\neffected through A. F. Fox Co.\n\n\nNinth Street Property for \u00a312,500.\nStone Fairfax sold, during the week,\nthe business property at 912 Ninth street\nnorthwest, for M. E. Frankiand and G.\nA. Gatrell, for $1250. The purchaser,\nwhose name was not made public in the\ntransaction, will probably erect a new\nbuilding upon the lot, which is 21 by 100\nfeet, and will occupy it himself. The\nprice of the property figures out about\n$6 a square foot.\nMoore Hill sold for the Loeffler es\ntate premises 457 and 49 New York ave\nnue and 447 M street. The consideration\nwas $10,500, and the purchaser in each\ncase will hold the property as an in\nvestment.\nAmong the residences sold was that\nfor William H. Walker, at 1442 Clifton\nstreet, for $9,500, which the purchaser\nwill occupy as his home. The house has\nthree stories, ten rooms, is of colonial\ndesign, and stands upon a lot 20 by 150.\nThe deal was made by Moore Hill\nThe same company scld for Jeremiah\nCullinane, premises 1108 New Hampshire\navenue northwest, at the intersection of\nthat avenue with Twenty-second and L\nstreets. The house is a three-story,\nbrick building, which was erected several\nyears ago by the late Gen. Sawyer for\na home, The purchaser will occupy the\nhouse as his home.\n\nApartment Houses Sold.\nShannon Luchs report the sale of the\napartment house at 642 Orleans place\nnortheast for Thomas H. Melton, builder,\nto party from West Virginia, who will\nhold the property as an investment. This\nis the third apartment house that this\nfirm has sold for Mr. Meltoh within the\npast month on the same street. The con\nsideration in the transaction was $3,500\n\n\nMoore Hill \u2018announce the sale of the\napartment house known as the Melwood,\nat 1770 U street northwest, for about\n$30,000. The sale was made for the owner,\nFranklin T. Sanner, the name of the pur\nchaser being withheld. The house is on\na lot \u00a32 by 100 feet, contains six suites\nof apartments, which bring an annual\nrental of $2,800,\nStone Fairfax have sold for M. 8.\nWoolf the two brick apartment houses\n\u2018at 767 and 769 Gresham street. Mr. Woolf\n\u2018bought the property a few months ago,\nand it is understood sold it at an ad\nyance,\nJohn Dayton has bought through the\noffice of N. L. Sansbury a lot of large di\nmensions, on Delafield street, Saul's Ad\ndition. Plans and specifications have been\nprepared, and Mr. Dayton will at once\nbegin the erection of a handsome resi\ndence, which he will occupy as his home\nwhen completed. The opening of spring\nhas given an impetus to building opera\ntions in this addition, and a large number\nof detached houses will shortly be in\ncourse of erection.\nM. H. Herriman has purchased, through\nBUILT BY C. W. KING. PART OF GROUND SOLD BY MOORE HILL AT $1 A SQUARE FOOT.\nOe i A Sc\nDeichman prepared the plans for the\nbuilding, and I. Pearson will construct it.\nA. Getz Son, builders, will erect for\nB. Daly one two-story brick house at 1312\nEast Capitol street, estimated to cost\n$8.99. C. A. Didden Son prepared the\nplans.\nW. P, McGee is preparing to erect four\ntwo-story brick houses at 266 and 272 Fif\nteenth street southeast, estimated to cost\n$16,000. J. H. Lewis prepared the plans\nand will superintend the construction of\nthe buildings.\n\n\nW. 8. Minnis will erect six two-story\nframe houses at 2618 to 262 Eleventh\nstreet rorthwest at an estimated cost of\n$25,000. J. J. Moebs is the architect and\nbuilder,\n\nJulius H. Durand has had plans pre\npared by Speiden Speiden, architects,\nfor a six-room frame residence in West\nWoodridge.\nDr. C. Cloves Fletcher will erect a resi\ndence on Twenty-fourth street, West\n\u2018Woodridge; two stories and basement;\nbrick foundation, frame superstructure.\nSpeiden Speiden, architects, prepared\nthe plans.\nMrs. Grace L. Jenkins has purchased\na site with frontage of thirty-five feet in\nPark road, and awarded a contract to L.\nE. Breuninger to erect a residence.\n\nThe Georgetown University Hospital has\n\u2018begun excavating for foundation of the\naddition to the hospital of brick and stone,\n30x60 feet, four stories and basement, to\ncost about $30,000. It is expected to have\nthe structure completed about November\n1. C. A. Didden Son prepared the plans.\nThe Mechanics\u2019 Savings Bank is having\nplans prepared by Harding Upman for\nbank and office building.\nMONEY LIES IN SUBURBS.\nReal Estate Agent Believes It Would\nPay to Build Houses in Broockiand.\nGrace M. Thomas, of the Corcoran\nBuilding, reports great activity in the\nsuburbs in all sections, especially Brook\nland. There are no vacant houses, and\napplicants call each day for homes to\nrent. She thinks it would pay some one\nto take advantage of the bargains in lots\nin that locality and erect houses to rent\nfor from $18 to $25 a month.\n\n\nThe extension of Monroe street and the\npossibility of the suburban cars going\nover the new bridge into the town will\nno doubt be a great benefit to all the\nproperty in that section. She hes already\nmade several sales to parties who are to\nbuild homes in the near future,\n\ni\n\n\nTHREE-STORY BUILDING ERECTED BY PP. J. NEE.\nP, J. Nee has found it necessary to enlarge his quarters at the southeast\ncorner of Seventh and H streets northwest. To this end he has had plans pre\npared by B. Stanley Simmons, architect, and a new building is now in course of\nconstruction, occupying the whole \u00a2f the lot adjoining the corner on H street.\nThe building when completed will be three stories high, with cellar, having a\nfrontage of 36 feet by a depth of 100 feet,\nThe building will be of the slow-burning type of construction, the floors\nsupported by steel columns and beams and the ceilings of stamped steel. A part\nof the first floor will be used as the office and shipping department, while the\nupper floors will be planned especially for the display of furniture.\nA large electric lift of the most modern type will be installed, together\nwith other modern appliances, to facilitate the cereful and rapid handling of\nthe stock proposed to be carried in this new structure,\nA. Koehler is preparing to erect a two\nNEW STORE IN SEVENTH STREET.\nFISHER CO. SELL LOTS.\nFlorence DD. McAuliffe Fuys Eighth\nSireet Property,\nThomas J. Fisher Co. announce an\nactive week, vome of their sales being as\nfollows:\nTo Florence D. McAuliffe, of the lot on\nG street southeast, between Eighth and\nNiath streets, fronting south thirty-six\nfeet. Mr. McAuliffe will erect on the\nproverty two houses for sale. The prop\nerty sold is the last piece in the block\nowned by the estate of A. C. Washburn,\nthe balance of the block having been sold\nduring the past few years by Fisher\nCo. to individual buyers, and nearly all\nof the Eighth-street frontage has been\nbuilt upon, every house being of a dif\nferent plan.\nTo E. 1. Goldshorough, a frontage of\n187 feet on the north side of Melrose\nstreet, in section 2, Chevy Chase, running\nback to the line of the Chevy Chase Club\nholding. The parcel contains over 16,000\nsquare feet, on which the purchaser will\nerect a residence,\n\nTo James J. Clark, the large lot located\nat the southwest corner of Connecticut\navenue and Irving =ireet, in section 2,\nChevy Chase, being 125 feet front on Con\nnecticut avenue and 125 feet on Irving\nstreet. The purchaser will at once have\nplans prepared for a house for his own\nuse.\n\nFor the Kennedy Davis Co. to\nC. T. Mcintyre, 1427 Ames street north\neast. Mr. Mcintyre will occupy the\ndwelling,\n\nOn the north side of Ames street, to\nMrs. George W. Emerson and Mrs. 8S.\nPepper, jointly, one of the Kennedy\nDavis Co.'s houses, to be heid as an\ninvestment.\n\n\n\nFor the Chevy Chase Land Company, a\nlot on the north side of Sheridan street,\nin section 3, Chevy Chase, to Edward J.\nEhrmantraut. The lot is 50 feet front by\n160 feet deep. The adjoining lot of the\nsame size they have sold to Harry C.\nKaufman. Both purchasers will build\nhouses for their own use as soon as\npayment in full hag been made on the\nlots,\n\n\nThree Jots on Taylor street, in section\n3, Chevy Chase, to Miss Fannle Cadel\nMiss Cadel already owns six lots in the\nsame block in this subdivision. The addi\ntional property is bought as a speculation,\nMiss Cadel hopes to build on the other\nportion of her holding in the near future.\n\nCITYSHOULD AWAKEN\nA Contributor Suggests Ac\ntivity on Several Lines.\nWOUID WELCOME CONGRESS\nRignald W. Beall Thinks as Long as\nMunicipality Is Dependent on Fed\neral Legislature It Should Show\nGratitude and Cultivate Favor,\nNceds of District Enumerated.\n\nBy RIGNALD W. BEALL.\nNo single interest has done so much\nfor upbuilding the National Capital as its\nnewspapers. It needs but the educational\ndevelopment imparted by them to awaken\nour citizens to the true proportions of\ntheir opportunity to build a great city.\nThe newspapers should not be afraid to\n RWEHEn us from our deep lethargy. It\nhas been said that when China is awak\n2 to her true greatness and her pos\n\n\n\n\nsibilities she will change the face of the\nglobe; so when the National City is\nawakened to her potential possibilities\nshe will surely become the queen city of\nthe world\u2014the pride and joy of all the\nnations.\nProgress is seen in every section of our\nalready beautiful city. We need to be\nmore appreciative of the things we have,\nand with a greater energy hustle for\nmore. If the expression may be par\ndoned, Washington ig \u201cbehind herself.\u201d\nShe does not measure up to 25 per cent\nof her possibilities. Our citizens need to\nbe educated to appreciate their opportuni\nties for their own and the nation\u2019s benefit,\n\nWashington Belongs to Nation,\nWashington as truly belongs to the na\ntion as to the citizens of the District of\nColumbia. The nation is vitally interest\ned in the beautification of every street\nand thoroughfare. Hundreds of thou\nsands more people from ithe States have\nvisited Washington within year than\never before to look upoh its noble public\nbuildings, broad avenues, historic statues,\nand its beautifu] parks. We need to show\nCong ess each year that we appreciate\nwhat it does for the benefit of the Capital\nCity. We need to educate our fellow\neitizeng and to court stronger favor with\n\u2018the men from the States who make our\nlaws and appropriate our money as they\nsee fit in the great white building on the\nHill,\n\n\nThe governmental machinery, with its\n40,000 officials, its Kepresentatives and\nSenalors, courts, and other public func\ntionaries, with their respective retinues\nof servants and retainers, is part and\nparcel of Washington. I repeat, the\naverage Washington business man does\nnot appreciate the government man, com\nmonly expressed as the government cierk,\nI do not like the word clerk, It should\nbe expressed inn some other form, like\n\u201cgovernment official\u201d or \u201can officer of\n\u2018the government.\u201d At the same time, the\ngovernment officials and the business men\nof Washington have never appreciated\nCongress, and they do not appreciate it\nNOW,\nOfficials Seem Familiar,\nRepresentatives and Senators are looked\n\u2018upon with a certain degree of familiarity,\n\u2018and not with that regard and respect due\nthelr high office. We know there are\nbut few men in the great army of gov\nernment clerks, as well as in Congress,\nwho do not measure up to that high\ngrade of manhood that wins the con\nfidence and respect of their fellow-men,\nbut from personal contact with a large\nnumber of government people in a busi\nness way, as a class, I must say they\n\u2018are possessed of higher capabilities and\na stronger sense of justice, with more\nintelligence, greater ambition for the bet\nterment of themselves and our common\ncountry, than can be found among any\nother working force on the face of the\nglobe.\nWhile members of Congress deserve the\nsame, and even more, confidence and re\nspect than those sacreq solons of ancient\nRome who sat in the senate and suffered\ndeath rather than depart one iota from\njustice and right, I must repeat that\nWashington does not appreciate the gov\nernment people; heither does it appre\nciate Congress.\nShould Work with Congress,\nThere is a great work to be done here,\nWe need to appreciate the government\npeople, and infuse into them a public\nspirited feeling of commen brotherhood\nin building up our \u201cGreater Washing\nreached the smaliness of the volume of\ntrade three years ago, To put it differ\nently, the effect of the recent stringency\nhas not put business back more than\nCiatinaed vn Page 3; Column 4,\nton.\u201d\n\nWe need to court closer favor\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK\nHOPEFULLY BRIGHT\nLiquidation Is More Than\nHalf Accomplished.\nBANKER GIVES VIEWS\nDeclares Conviction that In\nDeclares Convietion that In\ndustry Should Go Forward.\nProcess of Recuperation Now Well\nAdvanced Will Ge en with Ac.\ncelerated Momentum-\u2014Situation Is\nGood in Washington\u2014How Crops\nMay Affeet the Return of Full\nMeasure of Proseprity,\nMay Affect the Return of Full\nMeasure of Proseprity,\n\u201cFifty per cent of all liquidation pre\ncipitated by the stringency of last October\nhas been completed and is out of the way.\nThe remaining 5 per cent will be car\nried on slowly in such a way as not to\ncripple individuals, corporations, or\nbanks. The time has come, in my opin\nion, when business should go forward\nwith confidence, for nothing in sight and\nnothing prospective, barring disastrous\ncrop failures, could seriously affect the\nfinancial and industrial affairs of the\nUnited States within the next few\nmonths.\u201d\nThis statement appeared recently as the\nview of a prominent banker in Chicago,\nand seems to express the exact truth\nbriefly in regard to the business situation\nin the country generally, as well as in the\nchief center of the West. This banker\nsaid further that he expected the ligui\ndation, in securities especially, to con\ntinue for perhaps a year. He said that\nit was better for all concerned for the\nadjustment to take place gradually.\n\nRecuperation Well Advanced,\nBut the most hopeful view, eccording\nto this man, was that the process of re-\ncuperation had been going on steadily\nfor at least three months, and would \u00a30\non with Increasing momentum during the\nfurther work of liquidation. He thought\nthe recuperative process had become al\nready strong, sufficiently so as to give all\na cheerful confidence in the outcome.\nTaking a close view of conditions, as far\nas they were known to the Chicago\nbanker, they were in good shape for a\ncontinuous; and energetic activity, with\nout spurt or boom, until business men\nin all departments were given on solid\nground, with larger profits than can now\nbe realized.\nThis view of the present situation is\nconsistent, and essentially sound. In\nWashingion the retail merchants are en\ngaged in a spring trade that compares\nfavorably with former years. Several of\nthose prominent in business state that\nthe volume of trade is greater than it\nwas a year ago, and the profits not\nappreciably less. Anyhow, so far as the\nCapital is concerned; there is no reason\nfor discouragement.\n\n\n\n\nBanks on Sound Basis,\nEvery financial institution is on a sound\nbasis, no business failures of consequence\nhave occurred, trade is good, the real\nestate business is moving along well, lots\nare being sold, and new houses being\nbuilt as much as in former years. The\ndirection of things in Washington is es\nsentially forward. If some men are onlig\ned to work on a little narrower margin\nthan formerly, the disadvantage can be\novercome by patience and energy. The\nopportunities for expansion are not\nchanged by the money flurry of last vear.\nNo one will seek to deny the statement\nthat it is safer to launch upon some\nproject now than it would have been in\nthe seemingly prosperous times a year\nago.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nin Washington, so the outlook is\ngood the country over. Even the quad\nrennial bogy of the Presidential election\nis not a serious deterrent to business,\nIt probably affects the stock market and\nthe speculative industrial market more\nthan anything else; but business men,\nthe actual producers, are too busy to\nbother with politics, and they are giving\nattention to their factories, railrecads,\nmills, banks, and farms, seeking to derive\nthe best possible profits out of the coming\nsumme: Season.\n\n\n\n\nPanie Teaches a Lesson,\nOne \u00a2f the important lessons of the\nmoney stringency of last year was that\nthe banks were averse to allowing busi\nness feilure where it could be avoided.\nThis care over established business enter\nprises extended first to financial institu\ntions and then to the large Industrial\nplants, and so on to the smaller and less\nimportant ones. In other words, the\nbusiness community has effectually learn\ned the lessen that unity of effort will ac\ncomplish more than individual! action, and\nthat no business concern stands isolated\nin the modern world.\nOne of the effects of money stringency,\nas given by the Dry Goods Journal, fs\nthat wholesale and retail merchants are\nbuying less goods, holding smaller\nstocks, and reducing indebtedness as\nmuch as possible. In other words, the\ngreat business of the merchants is brought\na little nearer to a cash basis than it was\na year ago.\nCredits Are Shortened,\nIt appears that the time limit of credits\nhas been shortened. From the manufac\nturer to the country dealer money in a\nlittle smaller volume will flow at a more\nrapid pace along the river of trade this\nyear than last. But that is In itself\nhealthful. It is part of the process of\nliquidation, in which big stocks of goods\nare cleaned out, the shelves of stores filled\nwith new and most salable materials,\nmoney realized sooner, and bills more\npromptly paid. And it is to be remem\nbered that this accelerated speed in busi\nness is better than the immense volume\nof transactions carried on last year with\nlax credit and longer time of payment,\nHence it is a time to buy as much as can\nbe safely carried in stocks, for goods are\ncheaper now than they will be six months\nyear hence, when business has he\na\neel the thrill of larger demand.\ngun\nDry Goods Journal calls attention\npoint that is significant, It\nstates that while the volume of business\nThe\nto\nlast year, which was 2 record\nthis is smaller than it\nwas\nbreaking year, recession has not yet\nContinued on Page 2, Column 6,\na year and a half in the actual volume","height":"39896","width":"27624"}}
